<br>The file overflw is a ELF executable and have root SUID permission using which we can get we can get root access, if you are not familiar with SUID and GUID perm then you can have a look at this [blog](https://www.linuxnix.com/sgid-set-sgid-linuxunix/).

<br>Now to debug download [peda](https://github.com/longld/peda) if you already don't have and integrate it with GDB.
<br>Then transfer the binary file to our kali machine,for that I am using Base64

<br>The file has a **strcpy** function  which means we can do perform BOF on this.
![6](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/6.JPG)
<br>Now open the file in GDB and find offset and and check if there is any Security implemented
![7](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/7.JPG)
<br>**NX** (non-executable)bit is enable which means we can't put our shellcode inside it, so we need to find a way to exploit this, and I am also not sure if ASLR is enable or not because this is my machine and in this ASLR is off for this file, I will check that later on target machine. 
<br>Now open the file in GDB and run it.
![8](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/8.JPG)
![9](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/9.JPG)
<br>The program reach the break point now, create pattern and find the offset
![10](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/10.JPG)
<br>After creating the pattern run the program
![11](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/11.JPG)
<br>Once the program reach it's break point then press **c** to continue
![12](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/12.JPG)
![13](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/13.JPG)
<br>We got our offset @ **112**
<br>Now move back to the target server
<br>Open the file in **gdb**
![14](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/14.JPG)
<br>As you can see to check if ASLR (Address Space Layout Randomization) is enable, we can do this simple trick, first run the program and then check for system address **(0xb763a310)**, then run the program again and print the address of system again and you will be able to see the difference **(0xb75e5310)**, which is because the ASLR is enable and it change the address everytime the program runs, So no we have to bruteforce the address, in able to bypass **NX+ASLR** which is not that difficult in a 32bit OS.
<br>For bruteforce we need (system, exit and "/bin/sh") address respectively
![16](https://teckk2.github.io/assets/images/October/16.JPG)
<br>Note down all the address, and we need to align them in this order (system-exit-bin/sh) in little endian format.
<br>**System** = 0xb75e5310 
<br>**Exit** = 0xb75d8260
<br>**/bin/sh** = 0xb7707bac
<br> **little endian format** = "\x10\x53\x5e\xb7\x60\x82\x5d\xb7\xac\x7b\x70\xb7"

<br>Now using bash and python we can bruteforce for the address on that file, untill it matches our specified address, and soon we reach that point we will get root shell.

<br>c 'print "A" * 112 + "\x10\x53\x5e\xb7\x60\x82\x5d\xb7\xac\x7b\x70\xb7"');done
